Python and R

Cathy Nguyen

2021-05-09

Have you ever been on a team that prefers different coding languages? For example, I am accustomed to R, but my group project partner only understands Python. Wouldnt it be nice to have an interface where we can use both of our codes? Well, this is possible with reticulate. Reticulate embeds a Python session into an R session, which can streamline workflow. Isnt this incredible? First, we need to install the package reticulate.

library(reticulate)
py_install("seaborn")

I prefer tidying my data using dplyr in R. Its easy, but what if my partner wants the data to create graphs using Python?

EADA <- read_xlsx("EADA_2018.xlsx")
Texas <- EADA %>% filter(state_cd == "TX") %>% filter(str_detect(sector_name,"Public")) %>% select(institution = institution_name, city = city_txt, sector = sector_name, class = classification_name, student_aid = STUDENTAID_TOTAL, Revenue = GRND_TOTAL_REVENUE, expense = GRND_TOTAL_EXPENSE) %>% separate(sector, into = c("Public","College"),sep = ", ")
glimpse(Texas)

message <- "Please make it pretty. -Cathy"

We can create a python session in R markdown to perform the task. Its simple. Instead of writing R in the curly brackets, put python instead. We can import python functions during this session as well. You can also create secret messages for each other and keep a fun conversation going.

reply = "\nI got it! - T\n"
import seaborn as sns
sns.boxplot(x = "College", y = "Revenue", data=r.Texas)

As you can see, Python and R can work harmoniously together. All the components of our project can come together beautifully like a cinnamon roll hug.

cat(c(message, py$reply, "We finished! Yay!"))
## Please make it pretty. -Cathy 
## I got it! - T
##  We finished! Yay!
